<doc id="13093" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=13093" title="AMD files antitrust lawsuit against Intel in US federal district court">
<h1>AMD files antitrust lawsuit against Intel in US federal district court</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=AMD%20files%20antitrust%20lawsuit%20against%20Intel%20in%20US%20federal%20district%20court&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AAMD"&gt;AMD&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; filed an antitrust complaint against &lt;a href="Intel"&gt;Intel Corporation&lt;/a&gt; two days ago in &lt;a href="U.S."&gt;U.S.&lt;/a&gt; federal district court for the district of &lt;a href="Delaware"&gt;Delaware&lt;/a&gt; under Section 2 of the &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3ASherman%20Antitrust%20Act"&gt;Sherman Antitrust Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , Sections 4 and 16 of the &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AClayton%20Antitrust%20Act"&gt;Clayton Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , and the &lt;a href="California"&gt;California&lt;/a&gt; Business and Professions Code.

According to the complaint, Intel has unlawfully maintained its &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3Amonopoly"&gt;monopoly&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; by, among other things:

<ul>
BULLET::::- Forcing major customers such as &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3ADell%20Inc."&gt;Dell&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , &lt;a href="Sony"&gt;Sony&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AToshiba"&gt;Toshiba&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AGateway%2C%20Inc."&gt;Gateway&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , and &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AHitachi%2C%20Ltd."&gt;Hitachi&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; into Intel-exclusive deals in return for outright cash payments, discriminatory pricing or marketing subsidies conditioned on the exclusion of AMD;

</ul>
<ul>
BULLET::::- Forcing other major customers such as &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3ANEC%20Corporation"&gt;NEC&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AAcer%20%28company%29"&gt;Acer&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , and &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AFujitsu"&gt;Fujitsu&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; into partial exclusivity agreements by conditioning rebates, allowances and market development funds (MDF) on customers’ agreement to severely limit or forego entirely purchases from AMD;

</ul>
<ul>
BULLET::::- Establishing a system of discriminatory and retroactive incentives triggered by purchases at such high levels as to have the intended effect of denying customers the freedom to purchase any significant volume of processors from AMD;

</ul>
<ul>
BULLET::::- Threatening retaliation against customers for introducing AMD computer platforms, particularly in strategic market segments such as commercial desktop;

</ul>
<ul>
BULLET::::- Establishing and enforcing quotas among key retailers such as Best Buy and Circuit City, effectively requiring them to stock overwhelmingly or exclusively, Intel computers, artificially limiting consumer choice;

</ul>
<ul>
BULLET::::- Forcing PC makers and tech partners to boycott AMD product launches or promotions;

</ul>
<ul>
BULLET::::- Abusing its market power by forcing on the industry technical standards and products that have as their main purpose the handicapping of AMD in the marketplace.
</ul>
&lt;br style="clear:none;"&gt;
&lt;center&gt;
&lt;/center&gt; 
