<doc id="13611" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=13611" title="Underwater volcano erupts in Pacific near Japan">
<h1>Underwater volcano erupts in Pacific near Japan</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Underwater%20volcano%20erupts%20in%20Pacific%20near%20Japan&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;br&gt;
&lt;a href="w%3AJapan"&gt;Japan's&lt;/a&gt; coastguard reported Sunday that an underwater volcano had erupted in the eastern &lt;a href="w%3APacific%20Ocean"&gt;Pacific Ocean&lt;/a&gt;, about 1400 kilometers south of &lt;a href="w%3ATokyo"&gt;Tokyo&lt;/a&gt;. A plume of steam, rising more than 1100 meters into the air, was spotted by Japanese troops on &lt;a href="w%3AIwo%20Jima"&gt;Iwo Jima&lt;/a&gt;. Iwo Jima is located about 48 kilometers from the eruption.
Airborne Japanese officials and coastguard aircraft crews reported the water appeared brick-red. The survey crew also reported a grey, mud-like substance rising from the bottom. Video footage was taken. 
The last undersea eruption in the area was in 1986 and lasted three days.

